<p>This tutorial assumes that the reader has a basic knowledge of <a href=
=3D"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/c/socket-programming-cc/" rel=3D"noopener=
">socket programming</a>, i.e has a familiarity with basic <a href=3D"https=
://www.geeksforgeeks.org/system-design/client-server-model/" rel=3D"noopene=
r">server and client models</a>. In the basic model, the server handles onl=
y one client at a time, which is a big assumption if one wants to develop a=
ny scalable server model. The simple way to handle multiple clients would b=
e to spawn a new thread for every new client connected to the server.&nbsp;=
</p>
<p><a href=3D"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/operating-systems/semaphores-in=
-process-synchronization/" rel=3D"noopener"><strong>Semaphores:</strong></a=
> Semaphore is simply a variable that is non-negative and shared between <a=
 href=3D"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/operating-systems/thread-in-operatin=
g-system/" rel=3D"noopener">threads</a>. This variable is used to solve the=
 <a href=3D"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/operating-systems/critical-sectio=
n-in-synchronization/" rel=3D"noopener">critical section problem</a> and to=
 achieve <a href=3D"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/operating-systems/introdu=
ction-of-process-synchronization/" rel=3D"noopener">process synchronization=
</a> in the <a href=3D"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/operating-systems/diff=
erence-between-multiprocessing-and-multithreading/" rel=3D"noopener">multip=
rocessing environment</a>.</p>
<p><strong>sem_post: </strong>sem_post() increments (unlocks) the semaphore=
 pointed to by sem. If the semaphore's value consequently becomes greater t=
han zero, then another process or thread blocked in a sem_wait(3) call will=
 be woken up and proceed to lock the semaphore.</p>
<pre>#include &lt;semaphore.h&gt;
int sem_post(sem_t *sem);</pre>
<p><strong>sem_wait: </strong>sem_wait() decrements (locks) the semaphore p=
ointed to by sem. If the semaphore's value is greater than zero, then the d=
ecrement proceeds and the function returns, immediately. If the semaphore c=
urrently has the value zero, then the call blocks until either it becomes p=
ossible to perform the decrement (i.e., the semaphore value rises above zer=
o), or a signal handler interrupts the call.</p>
<pre>#include &lt;semaphore.h&gt;
int sem_wait(sem_t *sem);</pre>
<p>In this article, the <a href=3D"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/operating-=
systems/readers-writers-problem-set-1-introduction-and-readers-preference-s=
olution/" rel=3D"noopener">Reader-Writers</a> algorithm is implemented on t=
he server-side.</p>
<p><strong>Implementation: </strong>For the server-side, create two differe=
nt threads; a reader thread, and a writer thread. First, declare a <strong>=
serverSocket</strong>, an integer, a variable to hold the return of socket =
function.</p>
<pre>int serverSocket =3D socket(domain, type, protocol);</pre><ul><li><str=
ong>serverSocket:</strong> <a href=3D"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/c/socke=
t-programming-cc/" rel=3D"noopener">Socket descriptor</a>, an integer (like=
 a file-handle).</li><li><strong>domain:</strong> Integer, communication do=
main e.g., AF_INET (<a href=3D"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/computer-netwo=
rks/introduction-and-ipv4-datagram-header/" rel=3D"noopener">IPv4 protocol<=
/a>), AF_INET6 (<a href=3D"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/computer-networks/=
internet-protocol-version-6-ipv6/" rel=3D"noopener">IPv6 protocol</a>).</li=
><li><strong>type</strong>: Communication type.</li><li><strong>SOCK_STREAM=
</strong>: <a href=3D"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/computer-networks/tcp-i=
p-model/" rel=3D"noopener">TCP</a>(reliable, connection-oriented).</li><li>=
<strong>SOCK_DGRAM</strong>: <a href=3D"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/compu=
ter-networks/user-datagram-protocol-udp/" rel=3D"noopener">UDP</a>(unreliab=
le, connectionless).</li><li><strong>protocol</strong>: Protocol value for =
Internet Protocol(IP), which is 0. This is the same number that appears on =
the protocol field in the <a href=3D"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/computer=
-networks/introduction-and-ipv4-datagram-header/" rel=3D"noopener">IP heade=
r</a> of a packet.(man protocols for more details).</li></ul>
<p>Then, after initializing all the necessary variables <a href=3D"https://=
www.geeksforgeeks.org/c/socket-programming-cc/" rel=3D"noopener">bind the s=
ocket</a>.</p>
<p><strong>bind: </strong>After the creation of the socket, the bind functi=
on binds the socket to the address and port number specified in <strong>add=
r</strong>(custom data structure). In the example code, we bind the server =
to the local host, hence INADDR_ANY is used to specify the IP address.</p>
<pre>int bind(int sockfd, const struct sockaddr *addr,=20
         socklen_t addrlen);</pre>
<p><strong>listen: </strong>It puts the server socket in a passive mode, wh=
ere it waits for the client to approach the server to make a connection. Th=
e backlog defines the maximum length to which the queue of pending connecti=
ons for sockfd may grow. If a connection request arrives when the queue is =
full, the client may receive an error with an indication of ECONNREFUSED.</=
p>
<pre>int listen(int sockfd, int backlog);</pre>
<p>For more connection functions used in this article, please refer to this=
 article for socket programming in C.</p>
<p><strong>Approach:</strong></p>
<ul><li>After accepting the connection to the desired port, receive an inte=
ger from the client that defines the choice for reading or writing. Choice =
1 indicates reader, while choice 2 indicates writer.</li><li>After successf=
ully receiving data, call for pthread_create to create reader threads and w=
riter threads.</li><li>After making successful connections to the server-cl=
ient asks the user for input on the choice variable.</li><li>After getting =
the choice from the user, the client then sends this choice to the server t=
o call the reader or writer thread by creating a client thread for the requ=
est.</li></ul>
<p>Below is the implementation of the above approach:</p>
